            'autor' => 'Rafael Ogrim',
            'texto1' => 'God of War came again, and as much as he does not have a "4" in the name, is the official sequel to God of War 3. Announced for PS4 at E3 2016, the game took everyone by surprise by presenting the "antihero" Kratos now in Norse mythology, complete with a son and new powers. Forget the tough Kratos, destroyer of everything that appears in front of and wrong with life. In the new God of War we see a man almost "retired" and ready to face whatever the day offers ahead. The presentation which we follow the gameplay is almost the same view in the Sony conference, with few differences.',
            'texto2' => 'The demonstration starts almost the same way: Kratos speaks with his son in the cabin and takes him to hunt, to start learning their own way and bring food to the house. The two begin their journey together through the snow, and go in search of a deer or some other animal that serves to slaughter. The first thing to keep in mind here is: the new God of War is not an open world game, despite its scenarios have shown something in this direction. It has a huge map, but there is no free exploration, however it is not entirely linear as the previous saga. What we know is that Kratos will explore the map, but not the freedom to do whatever they want and whenever you want.', //3° paragrafos,
            'texto3' => 'The key to this is his son, for now just called "boy", yet unnamed. The boy followed Kratos throughout the demo, while the production team did not want to confirm that this would be a constant throughout the entire game. The most interesting, however, is that the child is to "hold" the human side of the old warrior, and also works as an extension to their skills. There is one in particular button on the control that allows the player to activate the child\'s passive skill, which varies according to the situation. During the same fight against the ice giant, the child throws a stunning arrow at the monster, which makes Kratos gaining an advantage in battle, even for a limited time. Further, situations like hunting together and search for items worked well using the two characters.', //4° paragrafos,
            'texto4' => 'The small detail that changes everything is that Kratos really cares about his son. Just as he cared about the other son, his Greek life, but now is even more evident. Despite losing patience with the young man when he does something wrong, the warrior logo note that was very rude, and tries to control. This relationship is a clear influence of games like The Last of Us, also exclusive PS4, which featured a similar relationship between the central characters Ellie and Joel. Here, however, we have a difference of young to be a little less active than Ellie girl, however we have the button that activates a passive skill. quote the fight is worth: forget the Olympus chains, at least in this demonstration. Kratos uses an enchanted ax and less rhythmical blows. The attack button works and responds well, you can combine moves to efficient results in enemies, but do not notice those totally exaggerated combos of God of War 1 through 3. Maybe later in the game, who knows?', //5° paragrafos
            'texto5' => 'Spartan of Fury is also there, but now carries in tune with the son of Kratos, somehow that little was explained. We note, however, that anger actually loads when the child is helping in battle, highlighted with the boss seen in the demo stage of the press conference Sony. Another detail worth to be named: the camera control. Say goodbye to fixed camera from past games. By having a more third-person perspective and on Kratos\' shoulders, the camera is moving almost entirely free, and it seemed very strange for a title of the saga. We do not know if the intention to inspire in The Last of Us may have gone too far, but it may be just usual question.', //5° paragrafos
